			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=110835&amp;sid=1b5cba79abef8878d9f58a7f35fb89b1#110835"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Tue Mar 29, 2005 4:26 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Setting up a proxy server</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=110835&amp;sid=1b5cba79abef8878d9f58a7f35fb89b1"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>     </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Is there any privacy in the corporate world? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Short answer? No.
<br />

<br />
Their property, their computers, their network, all time you spend there is <span style="font-style: italic">their time,</span> not yours. They <span style="font-style: italic">own</span> you, in a very real, legally binding sense. There have been lawsuits where employees have lost rights to the intellectual property they have created because it was done on company time. I even read one case where it was an employee's hobby project, done on his own time at home, but his employer was still able to take posession of it because his employment contract went so far as to claim ownership of everything he creates while employed. Some contracts stop just short of claiming they own your thoughts. I'd be willing to bet there are government and military contracts that don't stop there.
<br />

<br />
This is why you very carefully read your employment contract and all company policy before signing anything. You'll find the computer use policy typically revokes any kind of privacy right you think you have. This is all perfectly legal; if you don't agree with it, you can always refuse to sign. Signature is consent, and waives your rights.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
